  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is generally considered a **felony** in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions, to make it appear legitimate.\n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is a federal crime under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Significant fines** (up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds)\n- **Prison sentences** (up to 20 years per offense)\n- **Asset forfeiture** (seizure of property involved in the laundering scheme)\n\nThe severity of the penalties depends on factors such as the amount of money involved, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and whether the individual has prior criminal history.\n\nIf you are facing charges or have questions about money laundering laws, consult a qualified attorney for legal advice.",
